body:
@zheshipinyinMc, 

It seems that  your code has included the latency to convert image from fp32 to fp16. The conversion is not optimized so it might take a lot of time. Could you only measure the inference time?

If the problem still exists in inference time only. Could  you share the model? You can save the model in external data format, and only share the .onnx file and not weights in external data.

Possible causes:
(1) Some operator does not have GPU implementation. 
(2) float16 need new GPUs (like V100, t4 or A100), and not every GPU could get fp16 faster than fp32 in computation.

@tianleiwu
(1) onnxruntime is onnxruntime-linux-x64-gpu-1.8.1.tgz
(2) GPU is nvidia 1660
(3) onnx model is from https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Gh8C-bwl2B90RDrvKJkXafvZC3q4_H_z/view?usp=sharing
just measure inference time, fp16 also takes twice as long as float.
@tianleiwu I have tested other float 16 model in tensorrt, it is faster than float.

We use CuDNN library for Conv compute. 

One thing I did notice from the repro code is that, conv_search_algo is set to EXHAUSTIVE and that means on the very first Run, CuDNN does an exhaustive search of all the Conv algos to find the "best" based on the Conv weights/input descriptor. To dis-regard the effects of this, can you do a warm-up run for both fp16 and fp32  and compare the perf numbers ? The input to the second Run should be the same shape as the first input and if that is the case, the cached algo will be used from the second run. This will tell us if the gap between fp32 and fp16 is purely compute-tied.
@hariharans29 in repro code, calculate the time from the 101 run.

Thanks. We will have to investigate this when time permits.

Have you tried setting options.cudnn_conv_algo_search to `OrtCudnnConvAlgoSearch::HEURISTIC;` or `OrtCudnnConvAlgoSearch::DEFAULT;` ? Is fp16 atleast faster than fp32 then ?
@hariharans29 Having tried OrtCudnnConvAlgoSearch::HEURISTIC and OrtCudnnConvAlgoSearch::DEFAULT, fp16 is slower than fp32.

Will have to investigate this. 

One thing that jumps to mind is that currently, we potentially don't pick the best conv algo because we limit workspace size while picking the best conv algo - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/51f84a0330921c1e0f76a996cc404a1a1ed90f2b/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/nn/conv.cc#L252.

Using max workspace memory size is disabled by default and we currently don't have a way to turn it on for the end-user (it is in the backlog to enable it). If you can build from source, you may try making this one-line change (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/b876e5675badf515bb9a3948add3b7010a14c3c0/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/cuda_execution_provider_info.h#L53) and build from source.
for GPUUbuntu18.04 and x86_x64build command is  "./build.sh --config RelWithDebInfo --build_shared_lib --parallel"?
That builds only CPU. Please check here: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/build/eps.html#cuda for instructions on how to build ORT with CUDA enabled.

./build.sh --use_cuda --cudnn_home /usr/local/cuda --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda-11.0 --skip_submodule_sync
but got errors.
`CMake Error at CMakeLists.txt:627 (add_subdirectory):
  The source directory

    /home/workspace/onnxruntime_build/onnxruntime-1.8.1/cmake/external/googletest

  does not contain a CMakeLists.txt file.


CMake Error at CMakeLists.txt:629 (set_target_properties):
  set_target_properties Can not find target to add properties to: gmock


CMake Error at CMakeLists.txt:630 (set_target_properties):
  set_target_properties Can not find target to add properties to: gmock_main


CMake Error at CMakeLists.txt:631 (set_target_properties):
  set_target_properties Can not find target to add properties to: gtest


CMake Error at CMakeLists.txt:632 (set_target_properties):
  set_target_properties Can not find target to add properties to: gtest_main
`
And i found onnxruntime-1.8.1/cmake/external/googletest is empty. So is there a clear ReadMe about build from source?

AFAIK, that is the only doc we have. 

Did you clone submodules since you have `--skip_submodule_sync` (i.e.) did you run `git submodule update --init --recursive` ?
